SEARCH

All Classes and Interfaces

Class
Description
Algorithms<T>
Class Algorithms, implements Search and Sort interface and is used to complete many algorithms of arrays.
ArrayBreaker<T>
Class ArrayBreaker, implements interface ConversionTable which is used to get the row, column etc.
ArrayConvertor<T>
Class ArrayConvertor, implements interface SingleDimension and MultiDimension which is used to convert the single dimensional arrays into multi dimension and the multidimensional arrays into single dimension.
ConversionTable<T>
Interface ConversionTable, is implemented in class ArrayBreaker which is used to break the parts of the arrays of double and triple dimension.
LinkedList<T>
Class LinkedList, implements Queue and Stack interface and is used to complete FIFO (First-In-First-Out) technique to add and remove elements and FILO (First-In-Last-Out) technique to add and remove elements.
List<T>
Class List, the super class of LinkedList follows the technique of doubly linked list.
MultiDimension<T>
Interface MultiDimension, is implemented in class ArrayConvertor which is used to convert the single dimensional arrays into multi dimension.
Queue<T>
Interface Queue, is implemented in class LinkedList and is used to take in elements from the first index and remove elements from the first index, basically it works on FIFO (First-In-First-Out) technique.
Search<T>
Interface Search, is implemented in class Algorithms which is used to search the element in the array in sorted and unsorted arrays using Linear Search technique and Binary Search technique.
SingleDimension<T>
Interface SingleDimension, is implemented in class ArrayConvertor which is used to convert the multidimensional arrays into single dimension.
Sort<T>
Interface Sort, is implemented in class Algorithms which is used to sort the elements in the array in ascending and descending order using Bubble Sort technique and Selection Sort technique.
Stack<T>
Interface Stack, is implemented in class LinkedList and is used to take in elements from the first index and remove elements from the last index, basically it works on FILO (First-In-Last-Out) technique.
